### TITLE ###
LambdaSeesNarrowingWhenNotReassigned
### DESCRIPTION ###
A lambda defined under `if x != null:` captures x as `int` when
x is never reassigned in the enclosing scope. The narrowing
holds inside the lambda body.
### INPUT ###
fn outer(x: int?):
    if x != null:
        cb = fn() x + 1
        result = cb()
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> int?
  cb @ 3:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 3:19 -> int
  result @ 4:9 -> <no-type>
  cb @ 4:18 -> fn() -> int

# Symbol types
  cb (local): fn() -> int
  outer (fn): fn(int?) -> void
  result (local): int
  x (param): int?

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
LambdaDropsNarrowingWhenReassignedLater
### DESCRIPTION ###
A lambda defined under `if x != null:` should NOT see x as `int`
if x gets reassigned to null (or any other value) later in the
enclosing scope - the lambda may run after the reassignment.
Pyright's closure rule drops the narrowing; x inside the lambda
reads as `int?` (the base type).
### INPUT ###
fn outer():
    x: int? = 5
    if x != null:
        cb = fn() x
        x = null
        result = cb()
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:5 -> <no-type>
  x @ 3:8 -> int
  cb @ 4:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 4:19 -> int?
  x @ 5:9 -> <no-type>
  result @ 6:9 -> <no-type>
  cb @ 6:18 -> fn() -> int?

# Symbol types
  cb (local): fn() -> int?
  outer (fn): fn() -> void
  result (local): int?
  x (local): int?

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
LambdaKeepsNarrowingWhenReassignedBefore
### DESCRIPTION ###
A reassignment BEFORE the lambda's definition doesn't invalidate
the narrowing: by the time the lambda is defined, the new value
is the one being captured. The closure rule only drops narrowings
on paths reassigned AFTER the lambda.
### INPUT ###
fn outer():
    x: int? = 5
    x = 7
    if x != null:
        cb = fn() x
        result = cb()
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:5 -> <no-type>
  x @ 3:5 -> <no-type>
  x @ 4:8 -> int
  cb @ 5:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 5:19 -> int
  result @ 6:9 -> <no-type>
  cb @ 6:18 -> fn() -> int

# Symbol types
  cb (local): fn() -> int
  outer (fn): fn() -> void
  result (local): int
  x (local): int?

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
CompoundAssignAlsoTriggersRule
### DESCRIPTION ###
Compound assign (`x += 1`) counts as a reassignment for the
closure rule, just like plain `x = ...`. A captured narrowing
gets dropped when a later compound assign rebinds the path.
### INPUT ###
fn outer():
    x: int? = 5
    if x != null:
        cb = fn() x
        x += 1
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:5 -> <no-type>
  x @ 3:8 -> int
  cb @ 4:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 4:19 -> int?
  x @ 5:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 5:9 -> int

# Symbol types
  cb (local): fn() -> int?
  outer (fn): fn() -> void
  x (local): int?

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
ParamUnmodifiedKeepsNarrowingInLambda
### DESCRIPTION ###
Params have no Assign entries in the body (the binding is the
param slot itself, not an Assign), so a param that's never
reassigned in the body keeps its narrowing inside captured
lambdas. Common case - lambdas as map / filter callbacks.
### INPUT ###
fn outer(x: int?):
    if x != null:
        cb = fn() x + 1
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> int?
  cb @ 3:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 3:19 -> int

# Symbol types
  cb (local): fn() -> int
  outer (fn): fn(int?) -> void
  x (param): int?

# Diagnostics
  (none)
